<Pictures>None<//Pictures><Time>1516935278075< /Time><GmapID>0x809ad755d43ea705:0x7bd455ad0bd444ee<//GmapID>< Review>
I am posting negatively about a business for the first time ever. If I ever take the time to post it is usually for great customer service, or satisfaction.

Today I showed up at the royal oaks post office to have my passport reinstated. The time states that you can do this up until 6:30 in the post office, office. Mind you I understand I need to be there before that to actually get it taken care of. I got there at 6:15, and the doors were locked. There was an Asian man, not calling him a gentleman, behind the desk, right by the closed doors. I tried to open them three times and he didn't look up. I politely knocked, and no look. I decided to try to open the doors harder, maybe I was just mistaken by how the door opens? Nope, they were locked and the Asian man finally decided to glance up for two seconds to give me a disgusted look and point to the other double doors on the side of the building. He must've thought I was there to drop off mail.  I figured maybe as it nears closing time they only have those doors open. I go to the other doors and they are locked as well, but now he's far enough away to where him ignoring me does not seem unreasonable. I took advantage of the mail delivery window with the doorbell next to me, and used that to finally have an employee there speak with me. They started by abruptly saying it closes at 6 (I was now in the area of the post office that does), and the time was now around 6:18-6:20. I said I was there for my passport and that the office was closed and he was not paying attention to me. They fired back saying it takes about 20 minutes so they wouldn't be able to help. I was frustrated, so I do admit I snapped a bit and said that I was in the correct spot earlier but he didn't open the door or pay me any notice. Their last excuse was that he was having a bad day?! I ended up exclaiming that I just did not want my time to be wasted at this point and would appreciate them telling me if I at least have the correct paper work and documentation so that I could come back and take care of it. As this happened, i saw the Asian man walk back to the office to pretty much hide, I asked if i could talk to him about that to be sure, and the lady said she could help me as she does passports too. They did help with that, and I am forced to go back there to have it taken care of, but I have never been treated so rudely, and basically ignored to my face, because that person was having a "bad day" and did not want to work til the end of their shift?

Point of this post, if you can avoid royal oaks post office, do so. If you will be needing a person to person engagement, you will be taking the 50/50 chance that they are having a good or bad day, and that will determine the respect with which you receive. NOT WORTH IT!< /Review>

After 14 days I contacted the Royal Oaks Post Office on three separate days.  I was told it would be taken care of and I  asked to be called back for confirmation and they agreed to do so. < review>
I went to apply for a passport only to find that they will simply stop serving customers if the line is too long. I was there 1.5 hours before their scheduled close time and was turned away. There is no way of knowing when they will stop serving customers,  so I suppose you just have to arrive when they open if your schedule permits, which mine does not. When I complained to the worker, she rudely suggested that I go wait in another line to talk to a supervisor. Are you kidding me??
As an alternative, I tried scheduling an appointment at another post office and the phone number takes you to a voicemail where they ask you to leave a number and they'll get back to you to schedule the appointment. The problem is that they never get back to you.
There is no way a private company could stay in business if they offered such poor service. The post office should be privatized, as it would be doing the public a favor.<//review>

<Review>I came here on a Tuesday morning. Parking lot holds about 20 cars. 2 hour street parking. Mind you, limited parking for both doing business at the post office and passport office. Signs infront of the post office directs you towards the side towards the passport office. No public restrooms. Hours are actually 1030 - 1830 Mon - Sat. They do a ticket system. Plenty of chairs. All relevant infomation is on a table to the left as you enter. Employees seem too busy to help you personally. Waited from 1020, finished by 1130. I was number 4 in line. I saw 10 people waiting as I was leaving. Two employees for the whole 8 hours. I'd imagine fatigue and irritability gets to them as the day goes on. The guy seemed hating life. The gal was pleasant enough. Had everything ready: DS-11, birth certificate, ID. They photocopy your documents for you. They take your picture for an extra $15, and actually give you the extra headshot. They take cash, check, and debit. They only do DS-11 for passport applications. The actual process takes 10 minutes. The extra 30 - 60 minutes comes from waiting in line. I'd imagine everything becomes hell later in the day, but I can only give my impression from 1030 - 1130: not a terrible experience if you're there before lunch.<//Review><pictures>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMEss_1WzC7UBIn4PcZbUDPp9_no6zBmSpBsvW6=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]< /pictures>< resp>

<Rate>2</Rate>< text>
Had a package stuck in "missent/rerouting" hell for a week as it made circles between two post offices. Called the USPS, they said they'd investigate and get back to me.

2 days later, "Sammy" from the Royal Oaks Post Office calls to give me some news. Tells me to call him back - I call the number (the same one listed for this post office) and it rings, and rings, and rings ... 75 rings later, the phone company cuts off the call, as they do. No answering machine, no answer, nothing.

Then I try the two other numbers I can find for this same post office (one is the number caller ID lists the call came from). Same thing.

Finally, on my fifth call to the first number, someone picks up after 32 rings. And then promptly says "goddamn" and hangs up the phone on me before I can say anything.

They call me back the next day again, and rudely tell me "you were really hard to get ahold of." Really? Try answering your phone.

Not a friendly office - and they're not fulfilling their responsibilities to the parent organization, who now after my letter to the USPS OIG has to investigate why a staffer is giving out a number that they have no interest in answering.

I am a big fan of the USPS, but the staff of this post office give that organization a bad name.< /text>

<user_name>Morpheus Xzandersen<//user_name><date>1622920836932</date><Rate>2< /Rate>< Review>
Check You Credit Card Charges:
Decent place to wash... machines are usually clean and available unless it's rush hour.

Problem is that the machines will charge you more if you use credit card. I used $3.50 machine, it declined my first card but charged me $5 anyway without me knowing. i tried a second card and it worked but it also charge me $5 instead of the $3.50.

Use cash if you come here, it's a hassle trying to get this sort it out they think you are scamming then even though you show then the credit card texts showing the charges.< /Review>

< rate>
5</rate>
<Review>The laundry mat employees are typical two friendly ladies that will help you with any of the machines, if you need it. There is also a restroom located inside the building but you will need to have a quarter and an employee to let you in.

Washers and Dryers work great, and they have a variety of sizes for both uses. If you don't have or happen to forget soap/dryer sheets/fabric softener, don't worry, they have a vending machine inside that sells them all at your convenience. There is also a little mini arcade area with games kids can enjoy while waiting with their parents.

There is a good amount of seating and it wasn't that busy on a weekday night(4-6pm). Overall, great laundry mat.

P.S. A little tip, check the dryer machines for bent  metal that can possibly snag your clothes before putting your clothes in there. I only found one machine like that.</Review><pictures>None<//pictures>< Response>

< review>
First off, ignore the signs reading "24 hours." They failed at that and now are only open 24 hours on the weekend, but decided to not change the signs. Great people. They'll also close early whenever they want, so while they initially changed to closing at 2 a.m. during the week, that soon became 1, then midnight.
Second, when a machine fails, the employees will stare blankly right alongside you before realizing they're the employee and should probably figure something out.
I've gone here for about three years because it was the best option on the block, but I'm through with 'em now. Last time I went they said they were now closing early again, so I had to come back the next day. Then my washer got stuck on rinse cycle. Wish me luck elsewhere.</review>

Love this quaint, intimate theatre in the heart of downtown Chula Vista. < Text>
Had the most incredible experience today.
Tom greeted me with a smile and a friendly hello. First thing I noticed was how clean and organized the store was. Pricing was clearly marked and mattresses were arranged by brand and displayed neatly.
I explained to Tom how my boyfriend and I are home with 5 kids, and our old sleep number bed was not working for either of us. I went on to list ours must haves for a new mattress.. me with needing something supportive but plush, and him something that would keep him cool at night. Tom was able to find a perfect mattress for us, and made some other recommendations for add ons. (Like the waterproof mattress topper in case my potty training toddler sleeps over in our bed one night)
We were able to get some really great discounts due to my boyfriends military service, and Tom found the mattress I wanted at 50% from their warehouse. Walked out after my purchase with over $1,600 in savings and I am over the moon happy.
My biggest take away was the impeccable customer service, so thankful for Tom who fielded all of my questions and budget concerns.
Would recommend this place to anyone.
Make sure to tell Tom Betsy and Sean say thanks a million!< /Text>

After realizing my lumpy, super old mattress was in desperate need of replacing, I went to the Santee Mattress Firm store on my way home from work, anticipating to walk into a situation with a pushy salesman trying to sell me a mattress. Marco and Jesus showed up right on time, we‚Äôre friendly and efficient. My new mattress was set up within 10 minutes and they even got rid of my old mattress. < review>
I wanted to Thank everyone at Kindred for helping me recover from my tracheostomy which was a necessity after two intubations and CPAP/ Bipap not allowing my CO2 levels to normalize. I was very nervous at first and just having had to be tube fed with no voice, Patricia (nurse) made me comfortable right away with her upbeat sweetness. Learning how to care for a trach can be a process but luckily I had several good RT‚Äôs (respiratory therapists) to help. Heather was always offering knowledge and was quick to help out, Tiffany was thorough and watchful when I was afraid to try CPAP again ‚Äî she checked on me several times to make sure I was comfortable. Johanna was so encouraging even when I had a couple of hard days. Patrick took his time to answer all of the questions (which there were many).  I love Luis‚Äôs sense of humor and he was very upbeat. My original trach was too big:hence, the speak valve and eating/swallowing were out of the question until it was changed. Luis changed it with his partner in seconds making the process very easy. I have to say being bed bound at the beginning was not fun for me but Rosa, Rich, Bree along with many other nurses really helped me feel more dignified and took great care of me. I even got my hair washed which is very difficult with a new trach.   Henoch was extremely good with IV‚Äôs and NG tubes. Lupe was so quick, responsive and helped me greatly with everything from paperwork to mundane duties. She made a huge difference in my last few days at Kindred. My speech therapist ,Jojo,  was also very good: she made sure it would be safe to eat, drink before I started. She looked at my history and did tests accordingly.  I also could barely sit up when I first got to Kindred. Debra (my occupational therapist) first got me standing as well my physical therapists: Janice and Cesar after one week. Pretty soon we were standing and then walking. My other occupational therapist, Lauren, came back and she trained me on self care so I could go home. The doctors at this hospital are fantastic. Dr. Phan is so thorough and brilliant. His analysis of my blood work took care of problems I have had for over a year! Dr. Sandu whom performed my surgery (with Dr. Abudali another wonderful doctor) would follow up every other day on recovery status. Dr. Houramy is an extremely empathetic,spiritual, and sharp pulmonologist who came in with inspiring words frequently. He also really listened to my concerns and treated me accordingly. I absolutely thought the Infectious disease specialist Dr. Guiang was very thorough (of course) to make sure all the pneumonia was gone and she also came in with encouragement every day. Of course my patient advocates and case workers helped me greatly as well. Thank you Lisa, Mary, Lorilyn and Cindy!! Thanks to all of these people, I was able to come home, have a smooth transition. I am off oxygen at times and walking without any help at times (this is my 2nd day home). I am starting to do more and more for myself. I couldn‚Äôt have done this without the collaboration of all these hospital workers. I am very grateful. THANK YOU KINDRED!<//review>

< Text>
Newly opened areas for foot tragic flow; gives this place a welcomed new  feel!  Sunday's only 9am 5pm

No parking. Parking lot was full. If you can find one, street parking available.

Admission...$5

The line to get in was long. However, the line moved quickly and we were in!

100 +  friendly vendors offering you the best deal they can.

Live DJ Killing it!
And Various Music playing here and there as you stroll looking for those sleepers (hidden treasure)!

Shady areas to relax/ post.

Delicious Food trucks to fuel you when you get the munchies. And yes, Rest rooms available and clean.

If you enjoy:
A lively atmosphere.
Youthful spirited energy.
Friendly faces. And a barrage of clothing, vintage items, oddities, Art,  etc.

Then I'll see you there!< /Text>

This is the place to go to in downtown when you don't know exactly what you want to eat or when you're with a lot of people and you can't decide where to eat. This place is packed with flavor from different parts of the world. I was able to see Thai food, Chinese food, Salvadorian food, Mexican food, Italian food, and even vegan food (yes, I know vegan food isn't a part of the world but it deserves recognition as a food category haha). There are also little markets inside that sell produce, meat, spices, and candies. This place has it all!< /Review>

We love the Melrose Trading Post, it opens every Sunday on Fairfax, supporting the local High School.

There are so many vendors filled with creatives who‚Äôve come together to bring you affordable one of a kind pieces from; furniture to antiques, to jewelry, clothes, a shiatsu massage, crystals, vinyl records, dream catchers, plants... etc

There is a lovely square of food trucks and a live band.

Great place to go with friends, family, or with people visiting!</Text>

4<//rate>
< review>
This is a relatively fun, but small flea. It carries a $5 entry, but once you're in you're greeted with mostly vintage clothes, a few succulents and/or house plants vendors, some vintage print places, local Jewelers, vintage furniture, and a pretty great coffee place. It's more of a quirky outdoor home decor shop with a cover fee, but it does have its gems. Go here for clothing, or home decor. Don't come here for bargain hunting and lots of treasure hunting.< /review>

< Review>
Non-profit partnership between Greenway Arts Alliance and Fairfax High School to bring a flourishing community market, professional theatre and arts education/life programming to the Melrose & Fairfax neighborhood.
Awesome local & independent businesses, artists, musicians, designers, collectors and makers fill the market every Sunday.
Your $3 admission fee directly benefits students at Fairfax High.
Art & local commerce uplifting the community = everyone wins< /Review>

<rate>3< /rate>< review>
My first time at a flea market! There are two entrances ($3 each person). It's cash only, but if you don't have cash there is an ATM right by the entrance. Inside there are a lot of vintage items & stores that sell sunglasses, clothes, furniture, accessories, candles, food, & just some random items. Reminds me of an upscale outdoor swapmeet. It's only on Sunday's and it's just a fun spot to walk around! You may find a treasure or two!< /review>

<text>If you check the website, there's usually a coupon for $1 off entry.

Early bird def gets the worm here.  If you arrive early there's parking, but if you are like most of LA you aren't gonna get any parking, good luck with that!

As my friend says, it's like an outdoor goodwill, so you don't get the musty smells.  Are you spending an arm and leg on stuff you can get for a few dollars at Goodwill?  Probably!  But the goods are always unique and there are also almost always celebrities if that's your thing.

There is always awesome music in the food area.  And the food isn't bad either!  The guy in the corner doing corn bowls is awesome with delicious kombucha on tap.  Other notable eateries include the crepe place and there are always samples of fries.< /text>< pics>
None</pics>

<userid>115011152859120008322<//userid>< name>
Marc Regis< /name>
<Time>1519605833914<//Time>< Rate>
5< /Rate>
< review>
Its a street market showcasing local artistry and people's vintage finds. What other would call junk could also be another person's treasure. No shortage of old clothes and ornaments. There's a vendor there that has a whole department store section for aloha shirts for 7.00. Great fit for summer or for a gift for your trendy teen. It's bigger than you think so take the time to explore. Also, say hi to all the dogs you'll see. Came around 1:20, didn't find parking until 2:00 so I suggest coming early. There's also a mini street market across the street. It's a great Instagram photo spot due to the fact that there's an angel wing mural at the entrance of it. Great place to visit for 2 or so hours.< /review>

< Review>
Of the flea market offerings in LA, this is a big one.  However, the dominant item is clothes, clothes, clothes.  If you are looking for curated/vintage home goods or local artists, artisans, etc, this swap meet does have some, but they are few in number compared to the clothing offerings.  It's mainly a younger crowd, so whatever used-clothing trend is happening at the moment for that audience, you'll find a lot of here.< /Review>

< review>
A fun place to spend an afternoon, but less useful for making purchases. From my perspective, the household goods weren't very varied, well-priced or high quality, but may just not be my style. Great people watching and food trucks though and admission is only $3 per person. I'd really like to give this spot 3.5 stars.

< Text>
The hot spot for LA‚Äôs urban dwellers every Sunday, Fairfax High School parking lot is filled to the max of hipsters and kiosks ready to upscale your wardrobe or you interior decorating. Entry fee is under $5 and you can literally spend a whole day here checking out the shops, some live music and a delicious snow cone. Every trip to the Flea Market I walk away with new hand crafted jewelry or a groovy pair of sunglasses. Do yourself a favor and brave the parking to come wander around the asphalt, it will not disappoint.< /Text>
